    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c7fbf0c2_6d81e520",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1157909
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-11T19:26:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "How does this value work with paging?\n\nFor example, a user sends a request at 11:00, with max_staleness as 5 min, and then they send a subsequent request using the page_token from the first response at 11:05, with unchanged max_staleness. Will the results uploaded between 11:00 and 11:05 be included?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "e0dec1671bf9efd701d41170a91ba9492a61f6fa",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "08e517aa_e2026b20",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-11T19:34:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One way we could do it is store the time of first request in the page_token and use that for all subsequent pages requested. This would miss the results uploaded between 11:00 and 11:05, but would be consistent with how paging works in other places, namely, with no guarantees as long as the containing invocation is not finalized. I agree it\u0027s a little weird to think about and probably helpful to document explicitly in any case...",
      "parentUuid": "c7fbf0c2_6d81e520",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "e0dec1671bf9efd701d41170a91ba9492a61f6fa",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d3ef8bfb_c65d159b",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T00:11:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it works the same way as if we didn\u0027t have this field. In other words, this field has nothing to do with paging. Only controls the freshness of data we see in Spanner.\n\n\u003e For example, a user sends a request at 11:00, with max_staleness as 5 min, and then they send a subsequent request using the page_token from the first response at 11:05, with unchanged max_staleness. Will the results uploaded between 11:00 and 11:05 be included?\n\nyes\n\n-----------\n\nJao-ke, i think we discussed storing time in the page token in https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/infra/luci/luci-go/+/1888447/6/resultdb/internal/span/test_result.go#123\n\ntldr: maxStaleness cannot exceed 1h and https://aip.dev/158 recommends pageTokens to work for up to 3 days",
      "parentUuid": "08e517aa_e2026b20",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "e0dec1671bf9efd701d41170a91ba9492a61f6fa",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "72f754b8_690dde76",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T00:33:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right, we\u0027re not using/storing commit timestamp for ListTestResults, because it would add a lot of complexity without much added benefit, since we\u0027re relaxing guarantees for not-yet-finalized Invocations.\n\nI think \"max_staleness\" is somehow a weird way of putting it, since if something is \"stale\", I expect it to be too far in the past, rather than too recent, and it seems like what max_staleness does is say that \"if it\u0027s too recent we might not have those results yet\". Is that an accurate summary?",
      "parentUuid": "d3ef8bfb_c65d159b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "e0dec1671bf9efd701d41170a91ba9492a61f6fa",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c3fad2e2_e8144b84",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T17:14:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "this is an accurate summary and max_staleness is a rather standard term. I see 21K occurrences of \"max_staleness\" inside the google codebase. Here is usage of the term outside of google, in MongoDB: https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/blob/master/source/max-staleness/max-staleness.rst\nIt seems that many know what max_staleness means, and those who do might find a different term confusing (\"do you mean max staleness?\").\n\nI am happy to expand the comment to make things absolutely clear. Any specific suggestions for wording?",
      "parentUuid": "72f754b8_690dde76",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "e0dec1671bf9efd701d41170a91ba9492a61f6fa",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6fe3bdfb_a9381419",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/resultdb.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 157,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T20:35:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Fair enough, as it\u0027s too late to change the standard :) The standard was derived from describing the state of the secondary/replica more than the data, which is how we get this double-negative kind of description for the data (which, as it\u0027s append-only here, would be described more by freshness).\n\nMaybe \"The set of data from which the response draws is allowed to be stale up to this duration\"?",
      "parentUuid": "c3fad2e2_e8144b84",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 157,
        "startChar": 27,
        "endLine": 157,
        "endChar": 40
      },
